<ArticleTitle>Case comparison of sleep features from ear-EEG and scalp-EEG.</ArticleTitle>
<Pagination>
<MedlinePgn>69-72</MedlinePgn>
</Pagination>
<ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.slsci.2016.05.006</ELocationID>
<Abstract>
<AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">We investigate the potential usability of a novel in-the-ear electroencephalography recording device for sleep staging.</AbstractText>
<AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">In one healthy subject we compare simultaneous earelectroencephalography to standard scalp EEG visually and using power spectrograms. Hypnograms independently derived from the records are compared.</AbstractText>
<AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">We find that alpha activity, K complexes, sleep spindles and slow wave sleep can be visually distinguished using earelectroencephalography. Spectral peaks are shared between the two records. Hypnograms are 90.9% similar.</AbstractText>
<AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">The results indicate that ear-electroencephalography can be used for sleep staging.</AbstractText>
</Abstract>
